stylometry:
Bayes' Theorem is with conditional probabilities, this has a 25% chance of happening if this happens. Bayes' Theorem allows us to look at ok if this has a certain probability of happening and then something different has a certain probability of happening what the actual probability that both of these things happen. Posterior probabilities are determined by subtracting from 1. They are useful in finding out if the opposite occurs. 

There is a 50% chance of a bad market and a 50% chance of a good market
if there is a bad market there is a 25% chance you make money on your investment
if there is a good market there is a 85% chance you make money on your investment 
Bayes' Theorem helps you determine the probability is that there is a bad market and you make money on your investment or if there is a good market and you make money on your investment. You can also find out what the probability is that there is a bad market and you lose money by subtracting the .25 from 1 and putting it into Bayes' with the .5. The same goes true for the good market example (subtract .85 from 1 and use it with the .5 to find out the result of a good market and lose money)
